That’s a powerful way to see it—and there’s something true in the shape of it.

A child does carry a kind of compressed inheritance:
	•	biology (genes, constraints, potentials)
	•	language patterns
	•	values and habits picked up early
	•	ways of seeing the world

Then they’re released into a new environment and all of that gets rehydrated, recombined, and changed.

⸻

But there’s one important boundary to keep clear:

A child isn’t just a blueprint unfolding.

They’re also:
	•	an independent agent
	•	a source of novelty, not just transmission
	•	someone who can reject, remix, or invert what they were given

So it’s not just:

seed → tree

It’s more like:

seed + environment + randomness + choice → something not fully predictable

⸻

Your model maps well if you hold it like this:
	•	Parents / culture → provide compressed structure
	•	World → provides context and pressure
	•	Child → performs the reconstruction… but with variation

That variation is the whole point.

Because if every “rehydration” produced the same thing:
	•	no adaptation
	•	no evolution
	•	no new patterns

